I don=E2=80=99t give investing advice around here, but=C2=A0I have been bul=
lish on the Trump SPAC PIPE, the private investment in public equity deal  =
announced last month by=C2=A0Digital World Acquisition Corp., the special p=
urpose acquisition company planning to take Trump Media & Technology Group =
public. =E2=80=9CThe Trump SPAC PIPE Is Free Money,=E2=80=9D was  one Money=
 Stuff headline, which is sort of like a buy recommendation?=C2=A0And I sup=
pose that if Trump=E2=80=99s bankers at =E2=80=A6=C2=A0it says here EF Hutt=
on? =E2=80=A6 had called me up and offered me a slice of the deal, I probab=
ly would have subscribed for a bit.[1] But I see where these people are com=
ing from:More than a dozen well-known hedge funds and investment firms were=
 hesitant to go into business with Mr. Trump, people briefed on the matter =
said, because any association with him could risk alienating their investor=
s, which often include public pension funds and foundations. Others were wa=
ry of Mr. Trump=E2=80=99s history of corporate bankruptcies and disputes wi=
th lenders and partners, and concerned that details about his media company=
 were scant.At the moment, Trump Media =E2=80=94 which hired former Represe=
ntative Devin Nunes, a staunch Trump ally, as chief executive in December =
=E2=80=94 has no disclosed revenue or products.Among the funds that turned =
down Trump Media=E2=80=99s bankers were Millennium Management, a $57 billio=
n hedge fund; Hudson Bay Capital, a $15 billion hedge fund; and Balyasny As=
set Management, a $10 billion hedge fund. Apollo Global Management, the big=
 private equity firm, also passed, a person briefed on the matter said.Like=
, as a trade, on its own terms, the Trump SPAC PIPE is pretty good. You buy=
 some stock in Trump=E2=80=99s company at at least a 40% discount to the ma=
rket price, and you=E2=80=99re allowed to sell immediately into a frothy me=
me-stock market, or even to short sell now (if you can find stock to borrow=
) to lock in your profit. Page one of your investment memo is just =E2=80=
=9Cthis is a guaranteed 67% return if the deal happens.=E2=80=9D And then p=
ages two through 390 of the memo are about the risks that the deal doesn=E2=
=80=99t happen,=C2=A0the legal risks if the deal does happen and you get su=
ed for helping bash out this stock to retail investors,[2] the reputational=
 risks of that outcome, the reputational risks of funding whatever Trump=E2=
=80=99s=C2=A0media company gets up to,=C2=A0the risks of Trump trying to re=
cut the deal and take your profits away, and, yes, the market risks that ma=
ke that guaranteed return not=C2=A0quite=C2=A0guaranteed.[3]Still, free mon=
ey is free money, so the deal got done:Among the bigger investors: Pentwate=
r Capital, a $10 billion hedge fund in Naples, Fla., and Sabby Management, =
a hedge fund in Upper Saddle River, N.J., that manages more than $500 milli=
on, several people who were briefed about their involvement said. The amoun=
ts that Pentwater and Sabby invested couldn=E2=80=99t be learned.=E2=80=9CI=
nvestors have different risk preferences, including reputational as well as=
 financial risk,=E2=80=9D said Usha Rodrigues, who teaches corporate law at=
 the University of Georgia School of Law. =E2=80=9CIf the deal is sweet eno=
ugh, then the bankers will find someone who is likely to bite.=E2=80=9DAlso=
 here are some fun facts about the roadshow or whatever:In the days before =
Trump Media announced its $1 billion financing, the former president called=
 a handful of hedge funds, family offices and others who had signaled they =
would invest at least $50 million each, two people briefed on the matter sa=
id. The calls were intended as both a deal sweetener for larger investors a=
nd an opportunity for them to ask Mr. Trump questions about the start-up=E2=
=80=99s plans before they made plans to invest, several people said.Early o=
n, Trump Media bankers told some prospective investors that they would get =
a call from Mr. Trump if they put in $100 million, according to interviews =
with those investors. Later on, other investors were told that $50 million =
was enough for a call.It would be funny if they got a lot of orders for $49=
 million.One way to think about investing is that your essential job as an =
investor is to get paid to take some risk, and so the game is to figure out=
 what risks you like, the ones that you are=C2=A0especially well suited to =
take, that you can get paid well for taking, that you think are overpriced.=
 One way to analyze current markets is that there is a lot of demand for pe=
ople willing to take on=C2=A0reputational risk, so those people get paid we=
ll. (In other words: There are a lot of people who want to get rid of=C2=A0=
reputational risk, and so will pay well to get rid of it.) Reputational ris=
k is a hot asset class right now.This plays out  most visibly in environmen=
tal, social and governance investing, particularly the environmental side, =
where there is a lot of shareholder and political  pressure on big public e=
nergy companies to  divest their dirtiest assets. You can tell this story i=
n terms of financial risk, but for a lot of public-company executives it pr=
obably=C2=A0feels=C2=A0like a story of reputational risk, less =E2=80=9Cif =
we own coal mines our return on equity will go down=E2=80=9D and more =E2=
=80=9Cif we own coal mines my big shareholders will yell at me.=E2=80=9D=C2=
=A0If you are immune from that pressure =E2=80=94=C2=A0if you are a private=
 firm whose investors are not very ESG-conscious, a Middle Eastern state-ow=
ned energy company, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0then you can buy those assets cheap=
 and make a lot of money digging up dirty coal. Everyone more or less under=
stands this, but the gap is not arbitraged away, because those reputational=
 pressures=C2=A0are=C2=A0real. Most people do not want a bad reputation and=
 are willing to pay to avoid it. If people are paying to avoid a bad reputa=
tion, someone is getting paid.Or we  talked yesterday about how Microsoft C=
orp. was able to buy Activision Blizzard Inc. at a discounted price because=
 Activision had fallen into a deep reputational hole due to sexual miscondu=
ct allegations. =E2=80=9CWe=E2=80=99ll pay someone $20 billion to take our =
reputational risks away from us,=E2=80=9D Activision=E2=80=99s stock price =
effectively told the market, and Microsoft said =E2=80=9Chmm I think we can=
 do it more cheaply than that and pocket the difference.=E2=80=9D Which see=
ms like a good bet! Microsoft=E2=80=99s situation right now is in some sens=
e that it is the giant cash-rich tech company that is the=C2=A0most efficie=
nt bearer of reputational risk.[4] Here, read these two sentences:=09Facebo=
ok (sorry, Meta Platforms Inc.) just spent $69 billion buying a gaming comp=
any with a controversial=C2=A0chief executive officer facing allegations in=
volving a sexual misconduct scandal.=09Microsoft=C2=A0just spent $69 billio=
n buying a gaming company with a controversial=C2=A0chief executive officer=
 facing allegations involving a sexual misconduct scandal.I submit that whe=
n you read the first sentence (which is not true) you were like =E2=80=9Cug=
h, Facebook, are there any depths to which they will not sink,=E2=80=9D and=
 got all mad at Mark Zuckerberg. When you read the second sentence (which i=
s true) you fell asleep after the word =E2=80=9CMicrosoft.=E2=80=9D Microso=
ft has an ability to throw a thick blanket of boredom over scandals,=C2=A0w=
