   =20
      Information asymmetry
   =20
 =20
There is a certain kind of big investor =E2=80=94=C2=A0activist hedge fund =
managers, Warren Buffett, Elon Musk, Cathie Wood, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0who c=
an make a stock go up by buying it. If Warren Buffett buys 5% of a company=
=E2=80=99s stock, and then he says =E2=80=9CI bought 5% of that company=E2=
=80=99s stock because I like it,=E2=80=9D the stock will go up. Or if Bill =
Ackman buys 5% of a company=E2=80=99s stock, and then he says =E2=80=9CI bo=
ught 5% of that company=E2=80=99s stock because I want to do an activism,=
=E2=80=9D the stock will go up.=C2=A0When this happens:=09The investor =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0the activist or famous value investor or whoever =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0=C2=A0makes a quick profit, on paper. The investor also hopefully makes =
a longer-term, realized profit. If the investor buys at $50 and then announ=
ces her purchases and the stock goes to $60, she is up $10 per share, thoug=
h she is unlikely to sell immediately. (If you frequently do this and sell =
immediately, people are going to stop trusting you, and you will no longer =
be able to make the stock go up.) If the investor buys at $50 and then anno=
unces her=C2=A0purchase and the stock goes to $60 and then=C2=A0her thesis =
plays out=C2=A0=E2=80=94 she is right that the company is a good investment=
 and it continues going up, or she does activism and replaces the board and=
 the company becomes more valuable, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0and the stock goes =
to $80 and=C2=A0then she sells when her work is done, she makes $30 per sha=
re. But there is no guarantee of that; she might be wrong, or lose her acti=
vist campaign. The $60 quick-reaction price is roughly the market=E2=80=99s=
 estimate of the expected value of her involvement in the company.=09The=C2=
=A0other=C2=A0shareholders of the company also make a profit. Like the inve=
stor who catalyzes this, they have a quick paper profit (the stock goes up =
on the announcement) and then, if all goes well, a bigger longer-term profi=
t. But of course there is some risk of it not going well. They could sell a=
s soon as the investor announces her involvement and make the quick $10. No=
te that in any case the other shareholders make=C2=A0much more money=C2=A0t=
han our investor. If she buys 5% or 10% of a company=E2=80=99s stock and th=
en announces her ownership and the company=E2=80=99s value increases by $20=
 billion, she gets $1 or $2 billion of that, and the other shareholders get=
 the other $18 or $19 billion.=09The people who sold stock to our investor =
do not make much of a profit. I mean, they do fine; the stock was trading a=
t $50 and they wanted to sell at $50 and they sold at $50. Realistically if=
 our investor was buying a lot she probably pushed the stock up a little, s=
o the people who sold did a little better than they would have without her =
involvement. But they don=E2=80=99t get $60 per share; they don=E2=80=99t g=
et the price that they=E2=80=99d get after the investor announced her invol=
vement.This all strikes me as fine and good. The investor=E2=80=99s involve=
ment=C2=A0is valuable, so she gets to capture some of that value (Point 1).=
 She captures that value because she is providing value to others (Point 2)=
: Our investor=E2=80=99s involvement increases the expected value of the co=
mpany for all of its shareholders, and she gets a cut of that value roughly=
 proportional to her ownership. And people who don't own the stock =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0including people who were planning to sell anyway, and then did se=
ll =E2=80=94=C2=A0do not get much of that value (Point 3).Still there is in=
 the world an intuition, one that I find strange, that this is unfair to th=
e people who were selling. If they knew that our famous investor was buying=
 the stock, they would not have sold it to her for $50 (the pre-her-involve=
ment price); they would have demanded $60 (the post-her-involvement price).=
 There is an =E2=80=9Cinformation asymmetry=E2=80=9D: She knew that a famou=
s investor was buying the stock (because it was her, she was the famous inv=
estor buying the stock), and they did not (because stock trades are basical=
ly anonymous), so she is somehow unfairly taking advantage of their ignoran=
ce.You could imagine a rule that was like =E2=80=9Cif you are going to buy =
more than X% of the stock you have to tell everyone=C2=A0in advance so as n=
ot to take advantage of them.=E2=80=9D Or some variant on that. (=E2=80=9CI=
f you run more than $10 billion or have more than 100,000 Twitter followers=
 you have to disclose all your purchases in advance=E2=80=9D?) Or perhaps n=
ot in advance: A rule like =E2=80=9Cif you buy more than 1% of the stock th=
en you have to disclose that right away=E2=80=9D is=C2=A0almost=C2=A0as goo=
d as disclosure in advance, because it takes time to buy stock, so if you d=
isclose after the first 1% and you want to buy 5%, the people selling you t=
he remaining 4% will charge you more.In actual fact the rule in the U.S. is=
 a bit more complicated.[5] It says that if you buy more than 5% of the sto=
ck of a company, you have to tell people about that within 10 days=C2=A0aft=
er=C2=A0you get to 5%. In practice this means that you can keep buying for =
10 days after hitting 5% and get to, you know, 8% or 9% or more before tell=
ing anyone. For various other reasons activists often prefer to stay under =
10%, so for most activists this rule amounts to =E2=80=9Cyou can build your=
 whole stake secretly.=E2=80=9DAs I said, I find this fine and good, but ot=
hers do not. Securities and Exchange Commission Chair Gary Gensler for inst=
ance:=E2=80=9CI would anticipate we=E2=80=99d have something on that,=E2=80=
=9D Gensler said, adding that he is worried about =E2=80=9Cinformation asym=
metry,=E2=80=9D because the public doesn=E2=80=99t know there=E2=80=99s a b=
ig player buying up shares during the 10-day period.=E2=80=9CRight now, if =
you=E2=80=99ve crossed the 5% threshold on day one, and you have 10 days to=
 file, that activist might in that period of time, just go up from five to =
6% or they might go from five to 15%, but there=E2=80=99s nine days that th=
e selling shareholders in the public don=E2=80=99t know that information,=
=E2=80=9D Gensler said. =E2=80=A6=E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s material nonpublic i=
nformation that there=E2=80=99s an activist acquiring stock, who has an int=
ent to influence and generally speaking, there=E2=80=99s a pop if you look =
at the economics from the day they announced =E2=80=A6 there=E2=80=99s usua=
lly a pop in the stock at least single-digit percent,=E2=80=9D Gensler said=
. =E2=80=9CSo the selling shareholders during those days don=E2=80=99t have=
 some material information.=E2=80=9DWell, sure, the selling shareholders do=
n=E2=80=99t know who=E2=80=99s buying, which is material nonpublic informat=
ion, but it=E2=80=99s material nonpublic information that=C2=A0belongs to t=
he buyer. Or it does under current rules.=C2=A0A couple of points here. Fir=
st, the obvious losers from a rule change=C2=A0are activist hedge funds, wh=
o will need to pay more to buy their stakes and so will have lower profits.=
 But the other losers are=C2=A0non-selling=C2=A0shareholders of companies t=
hat activists would have targeted: Some number of activist campaigns will b=
e non-economical (because the activist would have=C2=A0to buy at a higher p=
rice), so the activists will do fewer campaigns, and since the activists=E2=
=80=99 campaigns generally generate more money for other shareholders than =
for the activists those other shareholders will lose out. The winners are t=
he=C2=A0selling=C2=A0shareholders, the ones who were happy to sell to the a=
ctivist at $50 but who now get to sell to her at $60.Second, I suppose this=
 is nice for those selling shareholders, but to be clear the people who rea=
lly want this rule change are corporate executives, who do not like to be s=
urprised by activists and want to make life as hard for them as possible. T=
he longtime advocates for this rule change have been Wachtell, Lipton, Rose=
n & Katz, the law firm where I once worked, which does a lot of activism de=
fense and has petitioned the SEC to shorten the reporting period for years.=
=C2=A0Third, the current rules allow investors to buy more than 5% economic=
 ownership of the stock using derivatives =E2=80=94=C2=A0total return swaps=
, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0without disclosing their positions; the rule requires=
 disclosure based on =E2=80=9Cbeneficial ownership,=E2=80=9D meaning mostly=
 owning actual stock. Ownership of large chunks of stock using swaps has fa=
llen into disrepute after last year=E2=80=99s  Archegos Capital Management =
blowup, and  the SEC has proposed requiring immediate disclosure of large s=
waps positions. So it is not surprising that it would also want immediate d=
isclosure of large stock positions.=C2=A0Fourth,  I find it weird that a lo=
t of people in financial markets have the following two intuitions:=09It is=
 bad for high-frequency traders to see what investors are doing and =E2=80=
=9Cfront-run=E2=80=9D their trades, in some loose sense.=09It is bad for bi=
g investors to have an =E2=80=9Cinformation asymmetry=E2=80=9D where they k=
now what they are buying but the market does not.Like in some sense either =
you own your own trading intentions or you don=E2=80=99t. Either you should=
 have to tell everyone about your trading plans so you don't have some unfa=
ir advantage over them, or you should be able to keep your trading plans se=
cret so that no one else can take advantage of them.=C2=A0
