   =20
      Insider trading cops
   =20
 =20
Occasionally Securities and Exchange Commission employees or investment-ban=
k compliance officers will get arrested for insider trading and their trade=
craft is always disappointing. =E2=80=9CYou worked in compliance,=E2=80=9D =
I want to say to them,=C2=A0=E2=80=9Csurely you know how insider traders ge=
t caught, why were you buying short-dated out-of-the-money call options on =
merger targets in your own account?=E2=80=9D But of course this proves noth=
ing. Perhaps hundreds of compliance officers and SEC lawyers are merrily in=
sider trading away right now, but they=E2=80=99re doing it really well and =
not getting caught.[6] Perhaps being close to the machinery of insider-trad=
ing enforcement gives you the tools, and the desire, to get around that enf=
orcement.Being a Needham police officer on the other hand:BOSTON =E2=80=93 =
Three men were arrested [Wednesday] for allegedly conspiring to trade on in=
side information about a Massachusetts company=E2=80=99s planned acquisitio=
n of a California semiconductor company.David Forte, 58, of Acton; John You=
nis, 59, of Bristol, R.I.; and Gregory Manning, 59, of Needham, were each c=
harged with one count of conspiracy to commit securities fraud. The defenda=
nts will appear in federal court in Boston this afternoon.According to the =
charging documents, beginning in or around June 22, 2016, Forte - an office=
r with the Needham Police Department - obtained material non-public informa=
tion from a close relative who is a senior executive at Analog Devices, Inc=
. (Analog), a Norwood-based semiconductor company, about Analog=E2=80=99s p=
lanned acquisition of Linear Technology Corp. (Linear), a semiconductor com=
pany based in Milpitas, Calif. Forte allegedly passed the information to tw=
o close friends, Manning and Younis, who purchased shares of Linear stock i=
n the week leading up to the public announcement of the acquisition on July=
 26, 2016. Younis also allegedly purchased call options -which are a bet th=
at the price of a stock will increase prior to the expiration of the option=
 - and tipped a business associate to purchase Linear shares as well. After=
 the deal was announced, Manning, Younis and Younis=E2=80=99 associate alle=
gedly sold their Linear securities at a profit, and Manning paid Forte a ki=
ckback in appreciation for Forte=E2=80=99s stock tip.Here is the SEC case. =
I suppose that if you are a suburban Boston police officer you probably do =
not get a ton of exposure to the latest techniques in insider trading enfor=
cement. This is a fairly standard case as these things go, neither howling =
errors nor clever tradecraft, though I enjoyed this:Manning paid Forte seve=
ral thousand dollars in cash several weeks after the merger was announced, =
withdrawing the money when he deposited a bonus check from his employer.Whe=
n Manning handed Forte the cash, Manning said =E2=80=9Cgood trade,=E2=80=9D=
 or something similar, and David Forte understood the payment was in return=
 for the tip.Yeah when someone hands you a bag of cash and says =E2=80=9Cgo=
od trade=E2=80=9D you know what it=E2=80=99s for. But so does the SEC.
