Thanks![1] I mean, not really. I have a job that I like, and it would be a =
weird journalistic conflict for me to invest in the Trump SPAC. I too am co=
nstrained by reputational concerns.[2] When we first discussed the PIPE,  I=
 said =E2=80=9Cthis is an indirect way to do a big meme-stock offering to r=
etail investors, with some hedge funds standing in the middle and getting a=
 cut.=E2=80=9D If you are one of those hedge funds, are you an =E2=80=9Cund=
erwriter=E2=80=9D of that offering? Can the retail investors sue you if TMT=
G=E2=80=99s public disclosure is not entirely accurate? Will TMTG=E2=80=99s=
 public disclosure be entirely accurate? Etc.[3] Roughly speaking the main =
one is that you are allowed to short the DWAC stock now, which would lock i=
n a huge guaranteed profit, but you probably can=E2=80=99t actually do that=
 because stock borrow is limited and risky and expensive. You can sell the =
DWAC stock when it is delivered to you, and there=E2=80=99s a death-spiral-=
ish true-up pricing mechanism to ensure that you get stock that is worth mo=
re than you paid, but you are not technically allowed to sell short=C2=A0du=
ring the averaging period for that mechanism (see section 4.12 here) so the=
re=E2=80=99s some market risk. (I think you *are* allowed to convert a port=
ion of=C2=A0your PIPE preferred stock into common stock and then sell it =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0as I described  here =E2=80=94 but that could mess with the =
true-up mechanism too.) The idea is that if the stock holds up well from no=
w until a few weeks after the closing of the SPAC merger, and then cracks w=
hen all of the PIPE investors try to sell at once, the PIPE investors could=
 have some risk. Also, if you don=E2=80=99t short now, you are at risk if t=
he stock ends up below $16.67 per share after the close of the merger, sinc=
e your purchase price (40% below the market price) is floored at $10. This =
stuff also interacts with the other risks. What if you do manage to short s=
tock now at $80 per share, Trump finds a way to cut you out of the deal, an=
d you have to buy back the stock at $100?[4] One important sense in which t=
his is true is that Microsoft is a giant company that has in the past fough=
t bitter antitrust battles, but now nobody mentions it in the same breath a=
s Facebook/Meta or Google/Alphabet in antitrust discussions. So it is just =
a lower-temperature acquirer of weird assets than its competitors would be.=
[5] It is Section 13(d) of the Securities=C2=A0Exchange Act of 1934, and Ru=
le 13d-1.[6] Maybe they=E2=80=99re  shadow trading?=C2=A0
