or: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bo=
rder-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #=
ccc;">where these people are coming from</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"ma=
rgin: 16px 0;">More than a dozen well-known hedge funds and investment firm=
s were hesitant to go into business with Mr. Trump, people briefed on the m=
atter said, because any association with him could risk alienating their in=
vestors, which often include public pension funds and foundations. Others w=
ere wary of Mr. Trump=E2=80=99s history of corporate bankruptcies and dispu=
tes with lenders and partners, and concerned that details about his media c=
ompany were scant.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">At the moment, Trump Med=
ia =E2=80=94 which hired former Representative Devin Nunes, a staunch Trump=
 ally, as chief executive in December =E2=80=94 has no disclosed revenue or=
 products.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Among the funds that turned down=
 Trump Media=E2=80=99s bankers were Millennium Management, a $57 billion he=
dge fund; Hudson Bay Capital, a $15 billion hedge fund; and Balyasny Asset =
Management, a $10 billion hedge fund. Apollo Global Management, the big pri=
vate equity firm, also passed, a person briefed on the matter said.</p></bl=
ockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Like, as a trade, on its own terms, t=
he Trump SPAC PIPE is pretty good. You buy some stock in Trump=E2=80=99s co=
mpany at at least a 40% discount to the market price, and you=E2=80=99re al=
lowed to sell immediately into a frothy meme-stock market, or even to short=
 sell now (if you can find stock to borrow) to lock in your profit. Page on=
e of your investment memo is just =E2=80=9Cthis is a guaranteed 67% return =
if the deal happens.=E2=80=9D And then pages two through 390 of the memo ar=
e about the risks that the deal doesn=E2=80=99t happen,=C2=A0the legal risk=
s if the deal does happen and you get sued for helping bash out this stock =
to retail investors,[2] the reputational risks of that outcome, the reputat=
ional risks of funding whatever Trump=E2=80=99s=C2=A0media company gets up =
to,=C2=A0the risks of Trump trying to recut the deal and take your profits =
away, and, yes, the market risks that make that guaranteed return not=C2=A0=
<em>quite=C2=A0</em>guaranteed.[3]</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Still, f=
ree money is free money, so the deal got done:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"m=
argin: 16px 0;">Among the bigger investors: Pentwater Capital, a $10 billio=
n hedge fund in Naples, Fla., and Sabby Management, a hedge fund in Upper S=
addle River, N.J., that manages more than $500 million, several people who =
were briefed about their involvement said. The amounts that Pentwater and S=
abby invested couldn=E2=80=99t be learned.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=
=E2=80=9CInvestors have different risk preferences, including reputational =
as well as financial risk,=E2=80=9D said Usha Rodrigues, who teaches corpor=
ate law at the University of Georgia School of Law. =E2=80=9CIf the deal is=
 sweet enough, then the bankers will find someone who is likely to bite.=E2=
=80=9D</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Also here are some fun =
facts about the roadshow or whatever:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16=
px 0;">In the days before Trump Media announced its $1 billion financing, t=
he former president called a handful of hedge funds, family offices and oth=
ers who had signaled they would invest at least $50 million each, two peopl=
e briefed on the matter said. The calls were intended as both a deal sweete=
ner for larger investors and an opportunity for them to ask Mr. Trump quest=
ions about the start-up=E2=80=99s plans before they made plans to invest, s=
everal people said.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Early on, Trump Media b=
ankers told some prospective investors that they would get a call from Mr. =
Trump if they put in $100 million, according to interviews with those inves=
tors. Later on, other investors were told that $50 million was enough for a=
 call.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It would be funny if th=
ey got a lot of orders for $49 million.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One=
 way to think about investing is that your essential job as an investor is =
to get paid to take some risk, and so the game is to figure out what risks =
you <em>like</em>, the ones that you are=C2=A0especially well suited to tak=
e, that you can get paid well for taking, that you think are overpriced. On=
e way to analyze current markets is that there is a lot of demand for peopl=
e willing to take on=C2=A0reputational risk, so those people get paid well.=
 (In other words: There are a lot of people who want to <em>get rid of=C2=
=A0</em>reputational risk, and so will pay well to get rid of it.) Reputati=
onal risk is a hot asset class right now.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">T=
his plays out <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/2643=
1223.261630/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjE=
tMDctMDgvc29tZW9uZS1pcy1nb2luZy10by1kcmlsbC10aGUtb2lsP2NtcGlkPUJCRDAxMjAyMl=
