<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Information asymmetry</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There is a certain kind of big investo=
r =E2=80=94=C2=A0activist hedge fund managers, Warren Buffett, Elon Musk, C=
athie Wood, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0who can make a stock go up by buying it. If=
 Warren Buffett buys 5% of a company=E2=80=99s stock, and then he says =E2=
=80=9CI bought 5% of that company=E2=80=99s stock because I like it,=E2=80=
=9D the stock will go up. Or if Bill Ackman buys 5% of a company=E2=80=99s =
stock, and then he says =E2=80=9CI bought 5% of that company=E2=80=99s stoc=
k because I want to do an activism,=E2=80=9D the stock will go up.=C2=A0</p=
><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">When this happens:</p><ol style=3D"list-style=
-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin=
-bottom: 5px;">The investor =E2=80=94=C2=A0the activist or famous value inv=
estor or whoever =E2=80=94=C2=A0=C2=A0makes a quick profit, on paper. The i=
nvestor also hopefully makes a longer-term, realized profit. If the investo=
r buys at $50 and then announces her purchases and the stock goes to $60, s=
he is up $10 per share, though she is unlikely to sell immediately. (If you=
 frequently do this and sell immediately, people are going to stop trusting=
 you, and you will no longer be able to make the stock go up.) If the inves=
tor buys at $50 and then announces her=C2=A0purchase and the stock goes to =
$60 and then=C2=A0<em>her thesis plays out=C2=A0</em>=E2=80=94 she is right=
 that the company is a good investment and it continues going up, or she do=
es activism and replaces the board and the company becomes more valuable, e=
tc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0and the stock goes to $80 and=C2=A0<em>then s</em>he sel=
ls when her work is done, she makes $30 per share. But there is no guarante=
e of that; she might be wrong, or lose her activist campaign. The $60 quick=
-reaction price is roughly the market=E2=80=99s estimate of the expected va=
lue of her involvement in the company.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5=
px;">The=C2=A0<em>other=C2=A0</em>shareholders of the company also make a p=
rofit. Like the investor who catalyzes this, they have a quick paper profit=
 (the stock goes up on the announcement) and then, if all goes well, a bigg=
er longer-term profit. But of course there is some risk of it not going wel=
l. They could sell as soon as the investor announces her involvement and ma=
ke the quick $10. Note that in any case the other shareholders make=C2=A0<e=
m>much more money=C2=A0</em>than our investor. If she buys 5% or 10% of a c=
ompany=E2=80=99s stock and then announces her ownership and the company=E2=
=80=99s value increases by $20 billion, she gets $1 or $2 billion of that, =
and the other shareholders get the other $18 or $19 billion.</li>=09<li sty=
le=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The <em>people who sold stock to our investor</e=
m> do not make much of a profit. I mean, they do fine; the stock was tradin=
g at $50 and they wanted to sell at $50 and they sold at $50. Realistically=
 if our investor was buying a lot she probably pushed the stock up a little=
, so the people who sold did a little better than they would have without h=
er involvement. But they don=E2=80=99t get $60 per share; they don=E2=80=99=
t get the price that they=E2=80=99d get after the investor announced her in=
volvement.</li></ol><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This all strikes me as fin=
e and good. The investor=E2=80=99s involvement=C2=A0<em>is valuable</em>, s=
o she gets to capture some of that value (Point 1). She captures that value=
 because she is providing value to others (Point 2): Our investor=E2=80=99s=
 involvement <em>increases the expected value of the company</em> for all o=
f its shareholders, and she gets a cut of that value roughly proportional t=
o her ownership. And people who don't own the stock =E2=80=94=C2=A0includin=
g people who were planning to sell anyway, and then did sell =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0do not get much of that value (Point 3).</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"=
>Still there is in the world an intuition, one that I find strange, that th=
is is unfair to the people who were selling. If they knew that our famous i=
nvestor was buying the stock, they would not have sold it to her for $50 (t=
he pre-her-involvement price); they would have demanded $60 (the post-her-i=
nvolvement price). There is an =E2=80=9Cinformation asymmetry=E2=80=9D: She=
 knew that a famous investor was buying the stock (because it was her, she =
was the famous investor buying the stock), and they did not (because stock =
trades are basically anonymous), so she is somehow unfairly taking advantag=
e of their ignorance.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">You could imagine a r=
ule that was like =E2=80=9Cif you are going to buy more than X% of the stoc=
k you have to tell everyone=C2=A0in advance so as not to take advantage of =
them.=E2=80=9D Or some variant on that. (=E2=80=9CIf you run more than $10 =
billion or have more than 100,000 Twitter followers you have to disclose al=
l your purchases in advance=E2=80=9D?) Or perhaps not in advance: A rule li=
ke =E2=80=9Cif you buy more than 1% of the stock then you have to disclose =
that right away=E2=80=9D is=C2=A0<em>almost=C2=A0</em>as good as disclosure=
 in advance, because it takes time to buy stock, so if you disclose after t=
he first 1% and you want to buy 5%, the people selling you the remaining 4%=
 will charge you more.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In actual fact the r=
ule in the U.S. is a bit more complicated.[5] It says that if you buy more =
than 5% of the stock of a company, you have to tell people about that withi=
n 10 days=C2=A0<em>after=C2=A0</em>you get to 5%. In practice this means th=
at you can keep buying for 10 days after hitting 5% and get to, you know, 8=
% or 9% or more before telling anyone. For various other reasons activists =
often prefer to stay under 10%, so for most activists this rule amounts to =
=E2=80=9Cyou can build your whole stake secretly.=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"m=
argin: 16px 0;">As I said, I find this fine and good, but others do not. Se=
curities and Exchange Commission Chair <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombe=
rgbusiness.com/click/26431223.261630/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuY25iYy5jb20vMjAyMi8wMS=
8xOS9zZWMtZXllcy10aWdodGVyLWRpc2Nsb3N1cmUtZGVhZGxpbmVzLWZvci1oZWRnZS1mdW5kc=
y1idWlsZGluZy1iaWctc3Rha2VzLWluLWNvbXBhbmllcy5odG1s/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23=
cBab581b03" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank=
" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-=
width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backg=
round-color: #ccc;">Gary Gensler for instance</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CI would anticipate we=E2=80=99d have somethin=
g on that,=E2=80=9D Gensler said, adding that he is worried about =E2=80=9C=
information asymmetry,=E2=80=9D because the public doesn=E2=80=99t know the=
re=E2=80=99s a big player buying up shares during the 10-day period.</p><p =
style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CRight now, if you=E2=80=99ve crossed the=
 5% threshold on day one, and you have 10 days to file, that activist might=
 in that period of time, just go up from five to 6% or they might go from f=
ive to 15%, but there=E2=80=99s nine days that the selling shareholders in =
the public don=E2=80=99t know that information,=E2=80=9D Gensler said. =E2=
=80=A6</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s material nonpu=
blic information that there=E2=80=99s an activist acquiring stock, who has =
an intent to influence and generally speaking, there=E2=80=99s a pop if you=
 look at the economics from the day they announced =E2=80=A6 there=E2=80=99=
s usually a pop in the stock at least single-digit percent,=E2=80=9D Gensle=
r said. =E2=80=9CSo the selling shareholders during those days don=E2=80=99=
t have some material information.=E2=80=9D</p></blockquote><p style=3D"marg=
in: 16px 0;">Well, sure, the selling shareholders don=E2=80=99t know who=E2=
=80=99s buying, which is material nonpublic information, but it=E2=80=99s m=
aterial nonpublic information that=C2=A0<em>belongs to the buyer</em>. Or i=
t does under current rules.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A couple =
of points here. First, the obvious losers from a rule change=C2=A0are activ=
ist hedge funds, who will need to pay more to buy their stakes and so will =
have lower profits. But the other losers are=C2=A0<em>non-selling=C2=A0</em=
>shareholders of companies that activists would have targeted: Some number =
of activist campaigns will be non-economical (because the activist would ha=
ve=C2=A0to buy at a higher price), so the activists will do fewer campaigns=
, and since the activists=E2=80=99 campaigns generally generate more money =
for other shareholders than for the activists those other shareholders will=
 lose out. The winners are the=C2=A0<em>selling=C2=A0</em>shareholders, the=
 ones who were happy to sell to the activist at $50 but who now get to sell=
 to her at $60.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Second, I suppose this is n=
ice for those selling shareholders, but to be clear the people who really w=
ant this rule change are corporate executives, who do not like to be surpri=
sed by activists and want to make life as hard for them as possible. The lo=
ngtime advocates for this rule change have been Wachtell, Lipton, Rosen &am=
p; Katz, the law firm where I once worked, which does a lot of activism def=
ense and has <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26431=
223.261630/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud2xyay5jb20vc2VjdGlvbi0xMy1kLw/607f07ceef4b8524a=
319a23cBf8267a1d" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"=
_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-b=
ottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid;=
 background-color: #ccc;">petitioned the SEC</a> to shorten the reporting p=
eriod for years.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Third, the current r=
ules allow investors to buy more than 5% economic ownership of the stock us=
ing derivatives =E2=80=94=C2=A0total return swaps, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0with=
out disclosing their positions; the rule requires disclosure based on =E2=
=80=9Cbeneficial ownership,=E2=80=9D meaning mostly owning actual stock. Ow=
nership of large chunks of stock using swaps has fallen into disrepute afte=
r last year=E2=80=99s <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/cl=
ick/26431223.261630/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGV=
zLzIwMjEtMDctMjkvYXJjaGVnb3Mtd2FzLXRvby1idXN5LWZvci1tYXJnaW4tY2FsbHM_Y21waW=
Q9QkJEMDEyMDIyX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZ=
XR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjIwMTIwJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b852=
4a319a23cBb676e130" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=
=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;"> Archegos Capital Management blowup</a>, and =
<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26431223.261630/aH=
R0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMTItMTYvdGhlL=
XNlYy1oYXMtYmlnLXBsYW5zP2NtcGlkPUJCRDAxMjAyMl9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09=
ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIyMDEyMCZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ24=
9bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB182c1031" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" i=
temscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-deco=
ration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00=
0000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> the SEC has pro=
posed</a> requiring immediate disclosure of large swaps positions. So it is=
 not surprising that it would also want immediate disclosure of large stock=
 positions.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Fourth, <a href=3D"https:=
//link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26431223.261630/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmx=
vb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTQtMDQtMjMvcHJlZGF0b3J5LXRyYWRlcn=
MtZnJvbnQtcmFuLWJpbGwtYWNrbWFuLXMtYm90b3gtYnV5P2NtcGlkPUJCRDAxMjAyMl9NT05FW=
VNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIy=
MDEyMCZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBc714775d" i=
temprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"co=
lor: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; b=
order-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: =
#ccc;"> I find it weird</a> that a lot of people in financial markets have =
the following two intuitions:</p><ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; pad=
ding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">It i=
s bad for high-frequency traders to see what investors are doing and =E2=80=
=9Cfront-run=E2=80=9D their trades, in some loose sense.</li>=09<li style=
=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">It is bad for big investors to have an =E2=80=9Cin=
formation asymmetry=E2=80=9D where they know what they are buying but the m=
arket does not.</li></ol><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Like in some sense ei=
ther you own your own trading intentions or you don=E2=80=99t. Either you s=
hould have to tell everyone about your trading plans so you don't have some=
 unfair advantage over them, or you should be able to keep your trading pla=
ns secret so that no one else can take advantage of them.=C2=A0</p><table c=
