<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Insider trading cops</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Occasionally Securities and Exchange C=
ommission employees or investment-bank compliance officers will get arreste=
d for insider trading and their tradecraft is always disappointing. =E2=80=
=9CYou worked in compliance,=E2=80=9D I want to say to them,=C2=A0=E2=80=9C=
surely you know how insider traders get caught, why were you buying short-d=
ated out-of-the-money call options on merger targets in your own account?=
=E2=80=9D But of course this proves nothing. Perhaps hundreds of compliance=
 officers and SEC lawyers are merrily insider trading away right now, but t=
hey=E2=80=99re doing it really well and not getting caught.[6] Perhaps bein=
g close to the machinery of insider-trading enforcement gives you the tools=
, and the desire, to get around that enforcement.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16=
px 0;">Being <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26431=
223.261630/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuanVzdGljZS5nb3YvdXNhby1tYS9wci9uZWVkaGFtLXBvbGlj=
ZS1vZmZpY2VyLWFuZC10d28tb3RoZXJzLWFycmVzdGVkLWluc2lkZXItdHJhZGluZy1zY2hlbWU=
/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB5f72de70" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"ite=
mscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !i=
mportant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bo=
ttom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">a Needham police officer</a> on=
 the other hand:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">BOSTON =E2=80=
=93 Three men were arrested [Wednesday] for allegedly conspiring to trade o=
n inside information about a Massachusetts company=E2=80=99s planned acquis=
ition of a California semiconductor company.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;=
">David Forte, 58, of Acton; John Younis, 59, of Bristol, R.I.; and Gregory=
 Manning, 59, of Needham, were each charged with one count of conspiracy to=
 commit securities fraud. The defendants will appear in federal court in Bo=
ston this afternoon.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">According to the charg=
ing documents, beginning in or around June 22, 2016, Forte - an officer wit=
h the Needham Police Department - obtained material non-public information =
from a close relative who is a senior executive at Analog Devices, Inc. (An=
alog), a Norwood-based semiconductor company, about Analog=E2=80=99s planne=
d acquisition of Linear Technology Corp. (Linear), a semiconductor company =
based in Milpitas, Calif. Forte allegedly passed the information to two clo=
se friends, Manning and Younis, who purchased shares of Linear stock in the=
 week leading up to the public announcement of the acquisition on July 26, =
2016. Younis also allegedly purchased call options -which are a bet that th=
e price of a stock will increase prior to the expiration of the option - an=
d tipped a business associate to purchase Linear shares as well. After the =
deal was announced, Manning, Younis and Younis=E2=80=99 associate allegedly=
 sold their Linear securities at a profit, and Manning paid Forte a kickbac=
k in appreciation for Forte=E2=80=99s stock tip.</p></blockquote><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here is <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness=
.com/click/26431223.261630/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9saXRpZ2F0aW9uL2xpdHJl=
bGVhc2VzLzIwMjIvbHIyNTMxMS5odG0/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB4e370b8e" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
the SEC case</a>. I suppose that if you are a suburban Boston police office=
